#:blog{:title "Path Integrals and Datom Streams: History Is Primary"
       :date #inst "2026-03-07T09:30:00.000-00:00"
       :abstract
       [:p
        "Feynman's path integral treats evolution as a sum over histories. Datom systems record one realized history, then derive state by interpretation. Both are "
        [:strong "history-first"]
        " views of reality and computation."]
       :content
       [:section.blog-article
        [:div.section-inner
         [:article
          :$blog-title
          :$blog-date

          [:p
           "Path integral intuition clarifies why event streams are such a strong base abstraction: histories come first, derived state comes later."]

          [:h2 "The Path Integral Perspective"]

          [:p
           "In Feynman's formulation, an outcome amplitude is computed as a contribution from many possible histories, not a single privileged trajectory."]

          [:p
           "At a conceptual level:"]

          [:pre
           [:code
            "Outcome = sum over possible histories"]]

          [:p
           "The key shift is from object snapshots to temporal structure."]

          [:h2 "The Datom Perspective"]

          [:p
           "A datom stream records realized history as immutable events:"]

          [:pre
           [:code
            "d1 -> d2 -> d3 -> d4 -> ..."]]

          [:p
           "State is not stored as a mutable singleton. It is interpreted from bounded history."]

          [:p
           "Terminology note: "
           [:code "history prefix"]
           " means the initial contiguous segment of the event log. This is a standard distributed-systems concept used to compare node histories."]

          [:pre
           [:code
            "state = interpreter(history-prefix)"]]

          [:h2 "Where the Analogy Is Tight"]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "History is the primary object"]
           [:li "Observers/interpreters extract observables from history"]
           [:li "Causality constrains valid orderings"]]

          [:h2 "Where the Analogy Is Not Literal"]

          [:p
           "Path integrals operate over possible histories with complex amplitudes. Datom systems store one realized history with explicit causal metadata."]

          [:p
           "So this is a structural analogy, not an equation of physical and computational mechanisms."]

          [:h2 "Implication for System Design"]

          [:p
           "When history is primary, architecture becomes simpler:"]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "Append-only facts instead of mutable hidden state"]
           [:li "Deterministic replay and time travel"]
           [:li "Multiple interpreters over one substrate"]]

          [:p
           "This is exactly the Datom.world split between stream substrate and interpreter semantics."]

          [:h2 "Conclusion"]

          [:p
           "A practical summary is: "
           [:strong "computation is interpretation of causal history"]
           "."]

          [:p
           "That statement is compatible with event sourcing practice and with the path-integral style insistence that histories, not snapshots, are fundamental."]

          [:p [:strong "Related Reading:"]]
          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li
            [:a {:href "/blog/datoms-as-spacetime-events.blog"}
             "Datoms as Spacetime Events"]]
           [:li
            [:a {:href "/blog/blockchain-trilemma-bounded-observation.blog"}
             "The Blockchain Trilemma Is a Bounded Observation Problem"]]
           [:li
